<br>
To truly worship hate, one must by definition be constantly in disaccord with everything around them.  They despise all they come in contact with, seek to conquer or destroy that which will not bend to their will, and use whatever means necessary to accomplish this goal, be it power, money, or people.  Even the most devote follower would gladly destroy his/her god and take his place if possible.  The only thing that keeps them in-line is fear.  There can be no true respect among the denizens of hate, as respect grows from understanding and, if I'm not stepping too far, love.  If you despise all around you, you can not respect anything.  Rather, you tolerate until you can bend to your will.  As such, their society is built upon the knowledge of mutually assured destruction.  Order is imposed simply because they know that to step out of bounds is to be destroyed.  Unless, of course, you are the more powerful, in which case society's order will reflect your vision, until some more powerful yet supercedes you.  Such is the nature of hate.<br>
<br>
To this, you compare the Goddess of Love bringing about a &quot;Lovebringer&quot;, if such an object exists.  What would this item do, and what is the true goal of Love?  You seem to think it's to destroy and kill the evil races, which is a slap in the face of what love truly is.  Love seeks to guide, to show compassion, to nuture, not to destroy and maim.  A true disciple of the Goddess would seek by actions and words to show the Tier'dal the error of their ways, and the ultimate destructive nature of their &quot;God&quot;.  A lovebringer would change the hearts, not rend the flesh.  Compassion, tolerance, understanding, cooperation...these are the things that would be brought about by the kind of intervention you speak of the Goddess of Love making.<br>
<br>
Now, if that were to happen, what would Tunare's response be.  You seem to think she would take the side of evil, to correct the &quot;balance.&quot;  Again, I think you misinterpret her wishes, though I seek not to overstep my station by attempting to put words or thoughts into the mouth and mind of Tunare.  She is a goddess of balance and nature, true, but only goodness can achieve true balance.  A world touched by love would not be one of unbalance, just one devoid of chaos (though I do credit that you touch on this in the margin of your journal).  Though the races of Norrath would work together for the good of all, balance would still be maintained as all things age and die.  <br>
<br>
If I remember correctly, the initial problem at the creation was growth without decay.  With the introduction of death, balance was maintained and order restored.  This being the case, the only true thing that could truly disrupt the balance, and require Tunare to intervene, would be the ending of death, as this would clearly have world-ending effects, as anyone could clearly see.  A world that leaned toward love and goodness, True love, not the oppressive type often expounded by Paladins and Priests,  would not be a world unbalanced, as death remains.  And death is not evil, as it lifts us from this mortal coil to Tunare's gentle embrace.<br>
<br>
Now some may argue about the nature of Good/Evil, but that's a talk for another time.  But to compare the compassion of Good with the hate of Evil is not truly understand the definition and motivation of the two.<br>
<br>
